<Page x:Class="AsynAwaitExamples.Steps.Step21_SynchronizationContext"
      xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
      xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
      xmlns:vm="clr-namespace:AsynAwaitExamples.ViewModels"
      Title="Step 21 - SynchronizationContext">
    <Page.DataContext>
        <vm:Step21ViewModel/>
    </Page.DataContext>
    <ScrollViewer VerticalScrollBarVisibility="Auto">
        <StackPanel Margin="10">
            <TextBlock Style="{StaticResource HeaderStyle}" 
                       Text="Step 21: SynchronizationContext Deep Dive"/>

            <TextBlock Style="{StaticResource ExplanationStyle}" xml:space="preserve">SYNCHRONIZATIONCONTEXT: The invisible mechanism behind await's thread behavior.

When you write "await" in WPF, the code after await magically runs on the
UI thread. HOW? The SynchronizationContext captures the current thread
before yielding, then posts the continuation back to that thread.

Different frameworks have different contexts:
- WPF/WinForms: posts to the UI thread (DispatcherSynchronizationContext).
- ASP.NET Core: NO context (uses thread pool, so no deadlock risk!).
- Console apps: NO context (uses thread pool).

Understanding this explains: why await resumes on the UI thread, why .Result
deadlocks, why ConfigureAwait(false) prevents deadlocks, and why ASP.NET Core
doesn't have the same problems as WPF.</TextBlock>

            <Button Style="{StaticResource ActionButton}"
                    Content="?? Show current SynchronizationContext"
                    Command="{Binding ShowContextCommand}"/>
            <Button Style="{StaticResource ActionButton}"
                    Content="?? Context capture vs ConfigureAwait(false)"
                    Command="{Binding ContextCaptureCommand}"/>
            <Button Style="{StaticResource ActionButton}"
                    Content="?? How context causes deadlocks (explanation)"
                    Command="{Binding ExplainDeadlockCommand}"/>
            <Button Style="{StaticResource ActionButton}"
                    Content="?? Manual SynchronizationContext.Post"
                    Command="{Binding ManualPostCommand}"/>

            <TextBox Style="{StaticResource OutputStyle}" Height="280"
                     Text="{Binding OutputText, Mode=OneWay}"/>
        </StackPanel>
    </ScrollViewer>
</Page>
